      <p>Even though diesel gives better MPG, the current ${d.gap_ppl}p gap means diesel vehicles typically cost <strong>more per mile</strong> than petrol at similar tunes. This flips only when the gap closes below ~10p.</p>`;
  } else if (key === 'gap') {
    html = `<h2>↔️ Diesel vs Petrol Gap</h2>
      <div style="font-size:36px;font-weight:800;margin:16px 0">${d.gap_ppl}p</div>
      <p style="font-size:15px"><strong style="text-transform:capitalize">${d.gap_status}</strong> — ${d.gap_context}</p>
      <h3>Historical context</h3>
      <p>In normal UK markets, diesel trades <strong>3-8p above petrol</strong>. This covers the extra refining step and transport costs.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>&lt;5p:</strong> Narrow — unusual, suggests oversupply of diesel</li>
        <li><strong>5-10p:</strong> Normal range</li>
        <li><strong>10-15p:</strong> Elevated — some supply pressure</li>
        <li><strong>15-20p:</strong> Wide — significant market dislocation</li>
        <li><strong>&gt;20p:</strong> Very wide — often linked to geopolitical events or refinery outages</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Why it moves</h3>
      <p>Diesel prices respond faster to shocks because demand is dominated by haulage, heating oil, and agriculture — inelastic sectors that can't easily cut consumption. Russia's 2022 invasion of Ukraine pushed the gap to ~30p at one point.</p>
      <h3>What to do</h3>
      <p>If you're buying a new car and the gap is persistently &gt;15p, the MPG advantage of diesel evaporates. Hybrids and EVs start to look better.</p>`;
  } else if (key === 'permile') {
    html = `<h2>🛣️ Cost Per Mile</h2>
      <p style="font-size:15px">Running cost per mile at current national average prices, for different car/fuel combinations.</p>
      <h3>Petrol</h3>
      <table class="fp-modal-table">
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">Small car (55mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.petrol_small.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">Medium car (48mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.petrol_medium.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">SUV / large (38mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.petrol_suv.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>Diesel</h3>
      <table class="fp-modal-table">
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">Small car (65mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.diesel_small.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">Medium car (58mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.diesel_medium.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="text-align:left">SUV / large (45mpg)</td><td>${d.per_mile.diesel_suv.ppm}p/mi</td></tr>
      </table>
      <h3>How it's calculated</h3>
      <p>Cost per mile = (price in pence/litre × 4.546 litres per gallon) ÷ mpg. MPG values used are real-world averages, not manufacturer-optimistic figures.</p>
      <h3>For EV comparison</h3>
      <p>A typical EV at home-charging rates (~£0.08/kWh off-peak) runs at roughly 2-3p/mile. At public rapid chargers (~£0.79/kWh), closer to 20-25p/mile — sometimes more expensive than petrol.</p>`;
  }
  showFpModal(html);
}

// Close modals on backdrop click
document.getElementById('historyModal').addEventListener('click', e => {
  if (e.target === e.currentTarget) closeHistoryModal();
});
document.getElementById('sightingModal').addEventListener('click', e => {
  if (e.target === e.currentTarget) closeSightingModal();
});

// Escape key closes modals
document.addEventListener('keydown', e => {
  if (e.key === 'Escape') {
    if (document.getElementById('historyModal').classList.contains('active')) closeHistoryModal();
    if (document.getElementById('sightingModal').classList.contains('active')) closeSightingModal();
    const fp = document.getElementById('fpModal');
    if (fp && fp.classList.contains('open')) closeFpModal();
  }
});
</script>
</body>
</html>